==Staffordshire Hoard==
The [[Staffordshire Hoard]] was found in, well, Staffordshire. The [[Battle of Hatfield Chase]] took place in what is now Yorkshire. There is no way that the two spots can be "less than 15 miles" apart. The actual distance is closer to 80 miles. --[[User:Dbachmann|dab]] <small>[[User_talk:Dbachmann|(𒁳)]]</small> 11:57, 15 August 2010 (UTC)
:Ah. I've just removed: "At least an important part of the gold and silver pieces would constitute the gifts or helps sent to him from Rome by the Pope [[Boniface V]]. The Vatican has shown interest in buying the hoard in 2009.<ref>"'I’ve been told that the Vatican think it may be the lost treasure of St Edwin,' she  [Deb Klemperer, from the Potteries Museum in Stoke-on-Trent] told the Sunday Mercury. [...] 'St Edwin was killed in battle with King Penda of Mercia in 632 AD, and I think it is likely that it is his hoard'"  [http://www.sundaymercury.net/news/midlands-news/2009/12/20/staffordshire-hoard-is-wanted-by-the-pope-and-the-vatican-66331-25430111/2/ "Staffordshire hoard is wanted by The Pope and Vatican"] (Sunday Mercury, 20 December 2008), [http://www.birminghammail.net/news/top-stories/2009/12/20/midlands-museums-face-vatican-battle-for-staffordshire-hoard-97319-25433986/ "Midlands museums face Vatican battle for Staffordshire Hoard"] (Birmingham Mail, 21 December 2009).</ref>" - as it is already clear the the hoard, in contrast to Sutton Hoo, does not represent the "treasure" of an individual but the valuable bits of the weaponry & other military kit of a large number of individuals, none of which show the slightest sign of Italian style. Nor do the sources say that the Vatican has expressed an interest, they merely say that some spokesman in the UK has expressed the view that he's sure (most implausibly in my my view) that the Vatican would like to buy the hoard, or some of it.  In view of the comment above I think I'll cut the lot. [[User:Johnbod|Johnbod]] ([[User talk:Johnbod|talk]]) 23:55, 29 October 2010 (UTC)
